<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1324,283,1390]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,427,283,309]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Variation</emphasis>
. With the usual color variations in the pile and tomentum; the ocellar tubercle may or may not have black hair. In the female, the lobe on the eighth tergite is often black instead of ferruginous; the basal lobes on the vaginal furca may not be developed to the same extent as described and figured.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1324,283,1390]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,444,443,469]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Discussion</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[512,624,444,470]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">paratypes</typeStatus>
listed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Painter" box="[740,908,444,470]" pageId="21" pageNumber="70" refString="Painter, R. H. (1932) A monographic study of the genus Geron as it occurs in the United states (Diptera: Bombyliidae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 58, 139 - 167." type="journal article" year="1932">
Painter (
<number box="[839,900,444,470]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1932.0">1932</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
from Port Lavaca, Texas belong to 
<taxonomicName box="[264,376,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senilis">
<emphasis box="[264,376,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. senilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and not 
<taxonomicName box="[482,607,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis box="[482,607,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The two species are very similar and are separated only by the genitalia. In the male of 
<taxonomicName box="[593,716,524,549]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis box="[593,716,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, there is a small projection on the ventral margin of the gonocoxa, this is wanting in 
<taxonomicName box="[641,787,564,589]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis box="[641,787,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the females, the shape of the vaginal furca differs by the configuration of the arms of the lower half, in 
<taxonomicName box="[998,1124,604,629]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis box="[998,1124,604,629]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are narrow and slightly curved and without inward projecting arms (
<figureCitation box="[925,996,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1777,1801]" captionTargetBox="[385,1208,437,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[380,1213,431,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Geron vaginal furcae. 1, G. albidipennis Loew. 2, G. albipilosus Hall &amp; Evenhuis, sp. nov. 3, G. arenicola Painter. 4, G. argutus Painter. 5, G. borealis Hall &amp; Evenhuis, sp. nov. 6, G. confusus Hall &amp; Evenhuis, sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156843/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[979,996,644,670]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName box="[1119,1265,644,670]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenicola">
<emphasis box="[1119,1140,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1154,1265,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">arenicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are stout and straight, and there are prominent inward projecting arms (
<figureCitation box="[1092,1162,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1777,1801]" captionTargetBox="[385,1208,437,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[380,1213,431,1768]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Geron vaginal furcae. 1, G. albidipennis Loew. 2, G. albipilosus Hall &amp; Evenhuis, sp. nov. 3, G. arenicola Painter. 4, G. argutus Painter. 5, G. borealis Hall &amp; Evenhuis, sp. nov. 6, G. confusus Hall &amp; Evenhuis, sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156843/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[1146,1162,684,710]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Evenhuis" pageId="21" pageNumber="68" refString="Evenhuis, N. L. &amp; Greathead, D. J. (1999) Catalog of the bee flies of the world (Diptera: Bombyliidae). Backhuys Publishers, Leiden, xlviii + 756 pp." type="book" year="1999">
Evenhuis &amp; Greathead (
<number box="[405,466,724,750]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1999.0">1999</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName box="[656,811,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perplexus">
<emphasis box="[656,811,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. perplexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(then a 
<emphasis box="[922,1092,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">nomen nudum</emphasis>
) under 
<taxonomicName box="[1193,1323,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis box="[1193,1323,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on unpublished notes in this study regarding similar configuration of the male genitalia. The description of 
<taxonomicName box="[549,698,804,829]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perplexus">
<emphasis box="[549,698,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. perplexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tabet" box="[740,890,804,830]" pageId="21" pageNumber="71" refString="Tabet, A. B. [2001] Three new species of Geron from Idaho (Diptera: Bombyliidae). Journal of Basic and Applied Sciences (Tripoli), 6 [1998], 48 - 52. [The date on the cover is &quot; 1998 &quot;, but correspondence with Tabet confirmed that this part was not issued until June 2001.]" type="journal article" year="2001">
Tabet (
<number box="[820,881,804,830]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
fits the characters that distinguish 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and it is thus synonymized under it here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1324,283,1390]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,404,883,909]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Biology</emphasis>
. One record of parasitization is known. 
<bibRefCitation author="Purrington" box="[939,1323,884,910]" pageId="21" pageNumber="70" refString="Purrington, F. F. &amp; Evenhuis, N. L. (2001) A clearwing moth host (Lepidoptera: Sesiidae) for the bee fly, Geron argutus (Diptera: Bombyliidae). Entomological News, 112, 178 - 182." type="journal article" year="2001">
Purrington &amp; Evenhuis (
<number box="[1254,1315,884,910]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
recorded the first record of a species of 
<taxonomicName box="[757,831,924,949]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[757,831,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Geron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from a sesiid, 
<taxonomicName box="[1017,1281,924,949]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Synanthedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polygoni">
<emphasis box="[1017,1281,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Synanthedon polygoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in Oregon. Several larvae and pupae of the hosts were obtained from a low growing 
<taxonomicName box="[1255,1315,964,989]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Diphyidae" genus="Gilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonophorae" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1255,1315,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Gilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Rearing of pupae produced one 
<taxonomicName box="[671,848,1004,1029]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis box="[671,848,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Geron argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
pupa. The pupa characteristically has reduced cephalic spines and short abdominal hairs. Adults have been taken at flowers of 
<emphasis box="[264,957,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authority="Daucus" authorityName="Daucus" box="[264,709,1084,1109]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Chrysothamnus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viscidiflorus">Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus, Daucus</taxonomicName>
carota, Sphaeralcea
</emphasis>
sp., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authority="Heliotus" authorityName="Heliotus" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Haplopappus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sonoriensis">Haplopappus sonoriensis, Heliotus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[373,428,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">alba</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[442,663,1124,1149]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Eriogonum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polygonales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elatum">Eriogonum elatum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[679,960,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[679,859,1124,1149]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Nepeta" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cataria">Nepeta cataria</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[873,960,1124,1149]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Salsola</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
sp., and 
<emphasis box="[1070,1173,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Psorelea</emphasis>
sp. Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[299,425,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis box="[299,425,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were observed by the junior author hovering and bobbing over a patch of catnip (
<taxonomicName box="[354,531,1204,1229]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Nepeta" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cataria">
<emphasis box="[354,531,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Nepeta cataria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in Sedona, Arizona in the summer of 
<number box="[997,1059,1204,1230]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1988.0">1988</number>
. One female was seen landing and laying three eggs on the leaf axil of a plant; then it flew away. Attempts to rear the eggs failed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1324,283,1390]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,465,1323,1349]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[484,655,1323,1349]" name="United States of America" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[484,655,1323,1349]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">United States</emphasis>
